MissionCommands.Message: Okay, Aquarius; Houston. That attitude looks pretty good. How's Jack getting along?
He's getting along, all set to go.
[Jump into the CM, Jack will now start the EI-4+40 checklist]
[Open the Mission Pad -> Checklists -> Command Module/AOH -> Mission -> A13: CM EI-4+40 checklist, and RUN it]
[Complete the checklist. The checklist will set things up, configure both the CM and the LM for RCS hot fire check.]
[Switch back into the LM.]
Okay, Jack just reported that all thrusters fired on both rings.
Real fine. Real fine.
[Set Attitude Control, Pitch and Roll, Pulse; Yaw, Mode Control]
[Maneuver back to SM Sep attitude (0, 91.3, 0) and damp all rates, press DONE when complete.]
And SM Jett at 138:12.
Roger. Understand; that's SM Jett, 138:12. It's not that time critical, Jim.
Can we do it at any time, Joe?
I think so, but let me check. Aquarius, Houston. That's affirmative. You can jettison the Service Module when you are ready; no big rush, but any time.
Okay. Sounds good.
Aquarius, Houston.
Go ahead.
Roger. We recommend that you use the AGS for the separation maneuver, because we'd like to get the proper weight in for the DAP before we use the PGNS again.
Roger. We will. Stand by.
[The SM SEP will now be executed. Press READY to proceed.]
AGS / DEDA: Key 404+0E, 405+0E, 406+0E, and 470R.
[Switch into the CM]
[Switch back into the LM]

Ok, let us coordinate this. I (you the player), will say "MARK" when I start to translate UP. Jack will seperate the CM 1 second later and Fred will verify Jack hits the right switches. Once staged, I will translate DOWN for 1 second.
[Ready? You will first need to translate UP until you hear Jack shout "SM SEP!", and then  you will need to immediately translate down. Press MARK and immediately translate UP.]
SM SEP!
[Press DONE when maneuver is complete]
SM Sep.
Copy that.
[Use the LM ASA and center the SM in the forward window. Press ROGER when you see it]
Okay, I've got her, Houston.
Beautiful, beautiful.
And there's one whole side of that spacecraft missing.
Is that right?
Right by the - Look out there, will you? Right by the high gain antenna, the whole panel is blown out, almost from the base to the engine.
Copy that.
Yes, it looks like it got to the SPS bell, too, Houston.
Think it zinged the SPS engine bell, huh?
That's the way it looks; unless that's just a dark brown streak. It's really a mess.
Okay, Jim. We'd like you to get some pictures, but we want you to conserve RCS. Don't make unnecessary maneuvers.
[Feel free to take some pictures and maneuver during the next conversations. The conversation is for history, and will differ from what angles and details you see etc.]
Okay, Joe, I'm now looking down the SPS bell, and it looks - looks okay on the inside; maybe it is just a streak.
Okay. Copy that, Fred. Was the bell deformed on the outside or just nicked or what?
I think the explosion, from what I could see, Joe, had - had stained it. I don't know whether it did any actual deformation or not.
Okay.
Man, that's unbelievable!
[Continue to watch it, the mission continues at 138:12:46]
Aquarius, Houston.
Go ahead.
Roger. We want you to go to the Service Module Sep attitude.
Okay.
[Start to manuever back to the SM SEP attitude, 0, 91.3, 0. Damp the rates when there.]
And, Jim, when you have leisure to copy, I have your Noun 46 and Noun 47 DAP data load numbers.
Okay. Go ahead.
Okay. Noun 46, 31021; Noun 47, plus 25248 and plus 09050. Over.
Roger; 31021, plus 25248, plus 09050.
[Switch into the CM, we will perform some initial power up for the CMC and get it into standby mode]
[Set the numerics brightness]
Aquarius, Houston.
Go ahead.
Okay. We'd like to have Jack verify that the Pyros in Logic are Safe, and we'd like to remind him to do no further power-up of the CSM until EI minus 2 plus 30.
Roger. He reports that the Pyros are Safe, and we're standing by for 02:30.
Okay. Real good.
Well, I can't say that this week hasn't been filled with excitement.

Well, James, if you can't take any better care of a spacecraft than that, we might not give you another one. Hey, Jim; Houston. You might ask Jack, while he's down there, to take a peek through the telescope and tell us whether he can see any stars. Over.
[Enter the CM, and then look into the SCT scope. It is unpowered but you might be able to see some stars through it. Press DONE when this is complete.]
[Request the ENTRY PAD using the Crew Members -> REQUEST PADS -> REQUEST ENTRY PAD]
[PAD copied]
And, Aquarius; Houston. If you want me to read you the landing area summary, I'll do that.
Sounds good.

Okay. In the mid-Pacific landing area, the weather is good. The cloud cover is 2000, scattered; visibility, 10; winds 060 at 10; wave heights are 4 feet, and the altimeter 2986, if you care. Scattered showers less than 10 per cent of the area.

Recovery forces are as follows: the Iwo Jima will be at the touchdown point, the aircraft call sign will be Recovery 1, on station with swimmers on board. The - we have the constant g backup reentry area covered with the USS Hall, the Good Liberty Ship, and the other recovery aircraft whose call signs you may hear are Samoa Rescue C-130s.
Okay, fine. We have the Iwo Jima as the prime recovery ship.
That's correct.
Aquarius, Houston.
Hello there, Houston.

Hi! Jim, we - We've gone ahead and computed the CSM coarse align gimbal angles based on your being at the Service Module Sep attitude at the time that Jack cranks up the computer and - and coarse aligns the IMU. That is, we assume that you're going to be at roll, 0; pitch, 091; yaw, 0; and, if you concur on that, I'd like to pass up the angles for - for Jack to have.
Okay. I'll be there to the best of my ability.
Good show. You ready to copy?
[Press READY when you are ready to copy]
Okay. CSM coarse align angles: Roll, plus 161.57; Pitch, plus 016.36; Yaw, plus 003.39.
[COPY]
That's affirmative, and that's for his Verb 41 Noun 20 when he gets there.
Aquarius, Houston.
Go ahead.
Okay. You're Go to start powering up the Command Module.
Right-o. We're starting now.
[RUN the Mission Pad -> Checklsits -> Command Module/AOH -> Mission -> A13: CM EI-2+30 checklist]
[Complete the checklist]
And I'll be ready for your P27 update.
And I'm in Accept.
Okay. Understand you are in P00 and Accept.
And, Jack, you can go ahead with the IMU and optics powerup. Over.
Roger. It's in work.
[RUN the Mission Pad -> Checklists -> Command Module/AOH -> Mission -> A13: CM EI-2+15 checklist]
[Complete the checklist]
Odyssey, Houston. The uplink is going well. We have one more load to get in.
Okay. Real fine.
Okay. We're coming up on time for the coarse align, Jim, so you can hold your attitude real good. [Maneuver to SM SEP attitude and ensure no rates]
And, Odyssey, Houston. The computer is yours. You can press on.
[The next procedure is to Coarse Align the IMU with the angles given]
[DSKY: Key V41 N20E]
[Wait for alignment to complete]
[Press PRO to complete COARSE ALIGN]
Houston, Aquarius.
Aquarius, Houston. Go ahead.
Roger. He just did the coarse align. I'm going to the jettison attitude.
Copy that.
Aquarius, Houston. I copied that you - that he's completed the coarse align; he's going into the P52 now? Is that right?
Let me check. I think he is.
Okay. You're staying at your present attitude, aren't you?
Yeah. We'll - I'll stay in the present attitude.
Roger that.
[Next you will complete a P52 option 3 using the stars visible in the scope. Ensure the LM attitude is at SM SEP attitude with no rates.]
[Enter the SCT to test scope, then return to the cockpit]
[Perform a P52 opt. 3 until the torquing display (Noun 93) using the P52 AID: REFSMMAT checklist (RUN) or follow the P52 checklist manually]
[The mission will proceed when you reach the torquing display, N93. At this stage, CLEAR the checklist steps if you are using the RUN feature]
Okay, Houston. There's a star angle difference with stars 36 and 40.
How about that, baby!
And I'm maneuvering, Houston.
Roger that. Copy you're maneuvering to the LM Jett attitude. Is that right?
[Swigert/Lovell] That's affirm. [Swigert] I'm going to torque those gimbal angles.
Torque them, babe.
[Torque the gimbals and complete the P52 routine, return to P00]
Okay, Odyssey. You're suddenly ahead of the timeline. You can press on in the checklist, Jack.
[Maneuver towards the LM SEP attitude roll, 130; pitch, 125; yaw, 012.4]
[Jack will now finalize the final steps on the EI-2+15 checklist]
Odyssey, Houston.
Go ahead.
We'd like to have you turn the optics power off until you need them again
Optics power going off.
[Verify that the LM is in the LM SEP attitude]
[Maintain attitude and damp all rates, standby]
Okay, Houston; Aquarius. I am at the LM Sep attitude and I'm planning on bailing out.
Okay. I can't think of a better idea, Jim.
Okay. We're ready to proceed with hatch closeup. [Follow the next steps, they are part of the LM clouseout checklist.]
[IVT to CM. Press F4 and close the LM hatch]
[RUN the Mission Pad -> Checklists -> Command Module/AOH -> Mission -> A13: LM HATCH checklist]
[Complete the checklist]
Okay, Joe. Since we're ahead of the time line, can I proceed on and kind of punch off early, or do you want me to punch off at exactly 1 hour?
Jack, when you are comfortably ready to punch off, you can go ahead and do it.
Okay.
Odyssey, Houston. We just had a formal Go for LM Jett at your convenience. Over.
Okay. Thanks, Joe.
Okay, Odyssey; Houston. We're ready for you to bring the BMAGs On and Warm Up and all other things being equal, we'd like you to go through the LM Jett at - on the checklist you've got.
Okay. Will do.
[RUN the Mission Pad -> Checklists -> Command Module/AOH -> Mission -> A13: CM EI-1+20 checklsit]
Okay, Houston. We'll punch off at 141 plus 30.
Okay, Jack. We copy and we concur.
Okay, Houston. Do we have a Go for Pyro Arm?
Okay. Just copied that, and you are Go for Pyro Arm.
[Set the SECS LOGIC (2) to up]
10 seconds.
Five.
LM jettison.
Okay, copy that. Farewell, Aquarius, and we thank you.

Okay, Jack. We'll have a PAD for you in a few minutes. We're getting data now on the tracking, and although we suspect the changes from your preliminary PAD will be very small, we recommend that you hold off on initializing the EMS until we get you the final PAD. Over.
Okay. I can proceed with EMS check, can't I, Joe?
That's affirmative, Jack. You can go ahead with that.
[RUN the Mission Pad -> Checklists -> Command Module/AOH -> Mission -> A13: CM EI-55 checklist]
[Complete the checklist]
[Request a new Entry PAD using the Crew Members -> REQUEST PADS -> REQUEST ENTRY PAD]
[COPY]
[Maneuver to Moon Check. Place the Moon at the 36 degree mark on the forward window]
And, Odyssey, we're ready for you to warm up the BMAG number 2's at your discretion and we're curious whether the Moon check attitude is good. Over.
[RUN the Mission Pad -> Checklists -> Command Module/AOH -> Mission -> A13: CM EI-40 checklist]
[Complete the checklist]
Okay, Joe. The Moon is coming down to about 38 degrees.
Okay, real fine. How did the EMS check go, Jack?
EMS checked out okay...
Good deal.
Its been initialized and setting on Entry.
[RUN the Mission Pad -> Checklists -> Command Module/AOH -> Mission -> A13: CM EI-30 checklist]
[Complete the checklist]

[Continue the entry checklist: Mission Pad -> Checklists -> Command Module/AOH -> Lunar Entry -> LUNAR RETURN VEHICLE PREP. If you want to RUN it, press RUN and then skip all steps until you have started P61. Skip the unnecessary steps.]
Okay, Joe, are you watching - you and FIDO taking a look at our Noun 60 here?
Jack, FIDO says that okay.
Jack, Houston, your Noun 63 looks good to us also.
[Continue with the entry checklist]
I know all of us here want to thank all you guys down there for the very fine job you did.
That's affirm, Joe.
I'll tell you - We all had a good time doing it.
Odyssey, Houston. Over.
Go ahead.
Okay. At 10 minutes to 400 K, you're looking good; we're real happy with the trajectory, and a minute ago, we just lost contact with your friend Aquarius.
Okay. Where did she go?
Oh, I don't know. She's up there somewhere.
She sure was a good ship.
Hey, just as I said that, we got another burst of LM data, so I guess it's still ticking.
Odyssey, Houston. Your DSKY is doing all the right things. The G&N is GO. Over.
Okay. Thank you.
You have a good bedside manner, Joe.
Say again, Jack.
You have a good bedside manner.
That's the nicest thing anybody's ever said!
Sure wish I could go to the FIDO party tonight.
Yes, it's going to be a wild one.
Odyssey, Houston. Over.
Go ahead.
Okay; We just had one last time around the room and everybody says you're looking great.
Thank you.
Odyssey, Houston. Over.
Go ahead.
Okay LOS is about a minute or a minute and a half; in entry attitude, we'd like Omni Charlie, and welcome home. Over.
Omni C to Charlie [auto set].
Thank you.
Odyssey, Houston standing by. Over.
Okay, Joe.
Okay. We read you, Jack.
We're looking at the weather on TV and it looks just as advertised; real good.
[Ensure you are following the LANDING PHASE checklist]
We got two good drogues.
Roger that.
Odyssey, Houston. We show you on the mains, it really looks great.
[Recovery helicopters] Iwo Jima Control, this is [garble] Recovery. I have a visual bearing 190. Over.
[USS Iwo Jima] Iwo Jima; Roger.
[Recovery helicopters] Apollo 13, Apollo 13, this is Recovery. Over.
Go ahead.
Apollo 13. This is Recovery and your chutes look good.
[Photographic helicopters:] Photo-1. Splashdown at this time. The three chutes are displaced. They're in the water.
[This completes the mission. You can optionally go through the post landing checks. Good job and congratulations!]

Title: MISSION 23 - REENTRY
Description: The final leg of the journey is getting close. The crew will continue to execute the planned timeline and maneuvers, and prepares for a lunar reentry through Earths atmosphere.
BriefingText:
Primary objectives:
• to perform selenological inspection, survey, and sampling of
materials in a preselected region of the Fra Mauro formation;
• to deploy and activate an Apollo lunar surface experiments package;
• to further develop human capability to work in the lunar environment; and
• to obtain photographs of candidate exploration sites.

You can find the documnets needed here:https://www.nasa.gov/history/afj/ap13fj/a13-documents.html
